Weâ€™ll fully break down ğŸ‘‡

* `stringstream ss(s)`
* `getline(ss, token, ' ')`
* what `token` does
* how the rest of the code works

---

### ğŸ§  Problem Recap

Weâ€™re solving **Leetcode 290 â€” Word Pattern**
We need to check if a string `s` (like `"dog cat cat dog"`) follows a given `pattern` (like `"abba"`).

---

### ğŸ“œ Code

```cpp
bool wordPattern(string pattern, string s) {
    vector<string> words;
    stringstream ss(s);
    string token;
    int cntwords=0;

    while(getline(ss, token, ' ')) {
        words.push_back(token);
        cntwords++;
    }
```

Letâ€™s break this first part carefully ğŸ‘‡

---

## ğŸ” What is `stringstream ss(s);`

Think of this like turning your string into a **stream of characters**, similar to how `cin` reads input.

Example:

```cpp
string s = "dog cat cat dog";
stringstream ss(s);
```

Now `ss` is like a pipe containing:

```
"dog cat cat dog"
```

---

## ğŸ“¦ What is `getline(ss, token, ' ')`

ğŸ‘‰ `getline()` reads **from `ss` until it finds a space `' '`**
and stores that piece into `token`.

Syntax:

```cpp
getline(source_stream, destination_variable, delimiter);
```

* `source_stream`: `ss`
* `destination_variable`: `token`
* `delimiter`: `' '` (space character)

---

So with `s = "dog cat cat dog"`, this loop:

```cpp
while(getline(ss, token, ' ')) {
    words.push_back(token);
}
```

works like this:

| Iteration | token   | words vector after push_back |
| --------- | ------- | ---------------------------- |
| 1         | `"dog"` | ["dog"]                      |
| 2         | `"cat"` | ["dog", "cat"]               |
| 3         | `"cat"` | ["dog", "cat", "cat"]        |
| 4         | `"dog"` | ["dog", "cat", "cat", "dog"] |

When the stream runs out of text, `getline()` returns false and the loop stops.

At the end:

```
words = ["dog", "cat", "cat", "dog"]
cntwords = 4
```

---

Now this part:

```cpp
int n = pattern.length();
if (n != cntwords) {
    return false;
}
```

ğŸ’¡ If the number of words doesnâ€™t match patternâ€™s length â†’ it canâ€™t match one-to-one, so return `false`.

---

Next:

```cpp
unordered_map<string,char> mpp;
set<char> used;
```

* `mpp` maps **word â†’ character** (e.g. `"dog" -> 'a'`)
* `used` keeps track of **which pattern characters** are already assigned

---

### ğŸ” The main loop:

```cpp
for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
    string word = words[i];
    char ch = pattern[i];

    if (mpp.find(word) == mpp.end() && used.find(ch) == used.end()) {
        used.insert(ch);
        mpp[word] = ch;
    } else if (mpp[word] != pattern[i]) {
        return false;
    }
}
```

Letâ€™s go line-by-line here:

---

#### ğŸ§© Case 1:

`mpp.find(word) == mpp.end()` â†’ word not mapped yet
`used.find(ch) == used.end()` â†’ pattern character not used yet

â¡ï¸ So we create a new mapping:

```cpp
mpp[word] = ch;
used.insert(ch);
```

Example (step by step):

| i | pattern[i] | word  | mpp                        | used         | Action      |
| - | ---------- | ----- | -------------------------- | ------------ | ----------- |
| 0 | 'a'        | "dog" | { "dog": 'a' }             | { 'a' }      | new mapping |
| 1 | 'b'        | "cat" | { "dog": 'a', "cat": 'b' } | { 'a', 'b' } | new mapping |
| 2 | 'b'        | "cat" | already mapped             | { 'a', 'b' } | check match |
| 3 | 'a'        | "dog" | already mapped             | { 'a', 'b' } | check match |

---

#### ğŸ§© Case 2:

`else if (mpp[word] != pattern[i])`

If word was already mapped but to a **different** pattern character â†’ âŒ mismatch â†’ `return false`.

Example:

```
pattern = "abba"
s = "dog cat cat fish"
```

When `i = 3`:

* word = "fish"
* ch = 'a'
* mpp["fish"] doesnâ€™t exist yet, but 'a' already used by "dog" â†’ mismatch â†’ false

---

Finally:

```cpp
return true;
```

If no mismatch found, everything matches perfectly âœ…

---

### ğŸ§  Full Example Walkthrough

Input:

```
pattern = "abba"
s = "dog cat cat dog"
```

| Step             | i | ch  | word  | mpp (wordâ†’char)            | used         | Action      |
| ---------------- | - | --- | ----- | -------------------------- | ------------ | ----------- |
| 1                | 0 | 'a' | "dog" | { "dog": 'a' }             | { 'a' }      | new mapping |
| 2                | 1 | 'b' | "cat" | { "dog": 'a', "cat": 'b' } | { 'a', 'b' } | new mapping |
| 3                | 2 | 'b' | "cat" | match found                | same char    | ok          |
| 4                | 3 | 'a' | "dog" | match found                | same char    | ok          |
| âœ… Returns `true` |   |     |       |                            |              |             |

---

### ğŸŒ¸ In Simple Words:

* `stringstream ss(s)` â†’ makes the string behave like input.
* `getline(ss, token, ' ')` â†’ reads one word at a time, split by space.
* Each `token` is pushed into the `words` vector.
* Then we check whether the pattern characters and words map consistently (1 word â†” 1 char).

---

Would you like me to show a **dry run table** for a *false case* too (like `"abba"` with `"dog cat cat fish"`) to see where it breaks?


code :


class Solution {
public:
    bool wordPattern(string pattern, string s) {
        vector<string> words;
        stringstream ss(s);

        string token;
        int cntwords=0;

        while(getline(ss,token ,' ')){
            words.push_back(token);
            cntwords++;
        }
        int n=pattern.length();

        if(n!=cntwords){
            return false;
        }

        unordered_map<string,char> mpp;
        set<char> used;
        for(int i=0;i<n;i++){
            string word=words[i];
            char ch=pattern[i];


            if(mpp.find(word)==mpp.end() && used.find(ch)==used.end()){
                used.insert(ch);
                mpp[word]=ch;
            }else if(mpp[word]!=pattern[i]){
                return false;
            }
        }
        return true;
    }
};

tc- o(n+m)
sc-o(k)
ğŸ“ˆ Complexity
Time complexity: O(n + m) â€” We split the string of length m and then iterate through the pattern of length n.
Space complexity: O(k) â€” We use a hash map that stores at most k unique characters/words, where k is the number of unique characters in 
the pattern. In the worst case, k can be equal to n, but it is at most 26 for lowercase English letters.
